    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:387e9b45-2bd6-4d7d-a6e3-e924e87cc6d3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 69-year-old retired civil engineer who presents with a dignified but visibly fatigued appearance. He is moderately built, standing approximately 5'10\" and weighing around 185 lbs, with slightly sunken cheeks and a graying beard. He moves carefully, occasionally wincing with lower back discomfort. He reports progressive difficulty with urination over the past several months, including weak urinary stream, increased urinary frequency—particularly at night—and a sensation of incomplete bladder emptying. He has also noticed mild pelvic discomfort and general fatigue that he initially attributed to aging.\n\n{patientName} is a widower who lives alone in a suburban home. He has two adult children who live nearby and are actively involved in his care. He describes himself as an avid gardener and enjoys woodworking in his garage workshop on weekends. He is a non-smoker and drinks one to two glasses of wine occasionally on weekends. He walks for 30 minutes most mornings, though recently his lower back pain has reduced his activity level. He follows a mostly Western diet, high in red meat and dairy, and has modest vegetable and fruit intake.\n\n{patientName} worked as a civil engineer for over 35 years before retiring at age 65. He describes his former work as highly stressful and sedentary. Since retirement, he has made efforts to stay socially active through a local seniors' club and a weekly book group. He has a close-knit circle of friends but admits he tends to downplay his symptoms and delayed seeking medical attention, only presenting after his daughter insisted he visit his primary care physician.\n\nHis primary complaint prompted a digital rectal exam (DRE) by his GP, which revealed a hard, irregular nodule on the posterior lobe of the prostate. His PSA level was markedly elevated at 18.4 ng/mL. He was referred to urology for further evaluation and biopsy, which confirmed adenocarcinoma of the prostate with a Gleason score of 7 (3+4), staged at T2cN0M0. He is currently undergoing evaluation for treatment planning, including discussion of radiation therapy and androgen deprivation therapy (ADT)."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
